Go Go Curry is definitely one of the best Japanese curry shops in NYC. Wonderful sauce with a subtle sweetness, not too salty or spicy, just the right amount of everything. It’s pork based, so vegetarians/vegans should avoid. I don’t think they have any substitutes. There’s plenty of toppings to customize your curry though, so despite the lack of alterations to the curry, you can still have a different experience every time. Curries are served with cabbage (free to ask for more) that you can mix up with the curry and it’s totally delicious.  Katsu are usually fried to a perfect crispness. Chicken and pork are tasty, shrimp is crunchy and fresh, the tofu is surprisingly delicious and I recommend that for fans of tofu. And, today J was surprised by how delicious the vegetable tempura was. A small crisp, nice batter with vegetables chopped into indiscriminate pieces, and seasoned perfectly. There are cold toppings too, like pickled vegetables and natto if interested.  One complaint is mediocre packaging for take out. Everything is placed together, which makes their wonderfully crunchy katsu soggy within minutes.  To sum up, great curry. Delicious and consistent every single time.

You might be thinking, what is Japanese Curry?  I don't know the history behind it, but what this restaurant sells are meals with a fried Pork or Chicken cutler, with a brown curry sauce (mild,) white rice, a kielbasi sausage, a hard boiled egg,  a shrimp tempura, and a bean sprout salad.  Additional toppings include cheddar cheese and various pickled items.  The end result is very unique and very good.  Vegetarian options available.  The restaurant is small.
